Commentary: Starting off with my favourite outfit of the event: this dress is absolute perfection, especially the buttons down the front. I have limited myself to two pictures here; there are several more right at the end of the pictures slideshow.

PhotoDetails1: Photo by Dimitrios Kambouris/Getty Images for The Met Museum/Vogue
Commentary: Her hair and makeup are amazing too -- she has rose petals or something on her eyelids and I love it.

ImageTitle: 2022 Met Gala Co-Chairs Blake Lively and Ryan Reynolds
Commentary: Blake Lively probably had the best dress of the evening. I like the copper/blue combination when the train is released, and I think it works well for the Gilded Age theme (if not from a dress style perspective, and it is admittedly a little Art Deco with all the rectangles on the front.)

PhotoDetails1: Photo by Dimitrios Kambouris/Getty Images for The Met Museum/Vogue

Commentary: And with blue train. (N.B. The Gilded Age was a period of time in the late nineteenth century in America which was known for railroad companies. Having discovered this, I am now very sad that there was a real lack of steam-train-based imagery in the costuming.)

This photo is included for the benefit of Ryan Reynolds, who I was fairly disparaging of (and I know I wasn't the only one) because it looked like he'd really gone with a very lazy black suit. Closer examination revealed it to be brown velvet, and I think that needs to be wider known.

Michelle Yeoh gets featured because (a) I like green, (b) I like Michelle Yeoh, and (c) I'm not generally a fan of the off the shoulder sleeves, because they make me feel slightly nervous because it looks like the garment will fall off downwards, but this has enough visible structure with the bodice and the train to mitigate that.

PhotoDetails1: Photo by Dimitrios Kambouris/Getty Images for The Met Museum/Vogue
Commentary: There are three pictures of Michelle Yeoh because we are all allowed to have our particular favourites, and she is one of mine.
Having a retinue to manage her train, as is right and proper for a queen of cinema. (Don't tell me if she's actually a terrible person in real life, I don't want to know.)
This dude gets points for effort (and also for not being Jared Leto - some people were mixing them up.)
The cutouts on the sides of the pants were interesting, and it does look like the ~porcupine quills~ are relatively flexible, so it's possible he was able to wear this in a vaguely functional manner.
Three pictures for this one as well because it's pretty cool.
Bonus points for making an effort. Does kinda remind me of a teapot.
But it's definitely interesting and that's the main thing.

I thought this was a very tacky look at first, because green vinyl isn't really on theme, but then I found out that this is a man not a woman, and that makes it a much more interesting choice contextually, so I'm rating it a lot higher than I would have if he'd been a woman.
I still think it doesn't work with the theme, but points for challenging the clothes/gender paradigm.

This is another one that I disliked on first viewing, but it has really grown on me. I really like the way the designer has played with shading in this dress by making it a sort of plaid: the vertical black and white, and the horizontal white and grey. I especially like the way this is continued up to her face, with the shading contrast caused by her veil between the top and bottom halves of her face.

PhotoDetails1: Photo by Dimitrios Kambouris/Getty Images for The Met Museum/Vogue
Commentary: This is a better shot of the bodice, which continues the plaid theme. I like the vaguely casino/cards theme of the fascinator, and the contrasting colour of the flower.
Several shots of this dress too, because the cityscape around the cape was so cool. I don't actually know if this is New York, but I hope it is.
The circular structured hair style is also very cool.
This photo is in because it's futher proof that Gabrielle Union is clearly an immortal of some description. Also it's a cool dress.

PhotoDetails1: Photo by Dimitrios Kambouris/Getty Images for The Met Museum/Vogue
Commentary: I enjoy the architectural structured collar here. Someone said it looked very super-villain, which is not a criticism.
Big fan of the Older Women in Slouchy Pantsuits look, and Annie Leibovitz looks ridiculously comfortable and stylish here.

Respect for this very ideosyncratic look from someone who clearly has a style that she likes and continues to wear -- the cane and various hats appear in a lot of other photos of her (from my very brief research)
